collections.name: The Boy
collections.description:
The Boy – A Reflection on Childhood and Resilience
"The Boy" is an evocative artwork created in 2015, characterised by its intricate interplay of graphite details, piercing charcoal shadows, and textured acrylic. This powerful painting has garnered significant interest from art collectors across diverse regions, captivated by its raw emotion and compelling narrative.

The inspiration for The Boy stems from a deeply personal encounter experienced by the artist during a challenging period in their life. One Saturday in 2015, while on a reflective walk, the artist encountered an 11-year-old boy named Michael. Michael, living on the streets, shared his story: each day, he would rise early to beg for money, which he used to provide food for his ailing grandmother. Touched by Michael’s resilience and selflessness, the artist spent the day feeding Michael and ensuring his grandmother had food, an experience that profoundly shaped the creation of the boy painting.

collections.name: Madrid Through My Eyes.
collections.description: This collection is from my exhibition  "Madrid through my eyes". It consists of 24 paintings, ( most of them sold), Where I have given an insight into my artistic view of the city. I used to live in Madrid from 2002-2005. Which means I lived there in 2004 during the horrific incident where Al Quaida attacked Atocha station, ( also called  M-11) where 193 people got killed, and some 2000 injured. It affected me deeply. I made several paintings inspired of that event. I also witnessed a Skyscraper fire. (The Windsor tower) where luckily no one got killed.  But the pictures at the front page of the Spanish newspaper "El Pais", the day after, inspired me to make art.  The artwork is a mix of photography and acrylic paint, mixed with with volcanic sand.

collections.name: Corona Vista
collections.description: Who says you can’t create your own crown? Corona Vista, the latest Orangehare In-House Production, invites viewers to explore the power of self-expression through 120 unique 1-of-1 NFTs. Drawing from the Latin roots of its name—Corona meaning “Crown” and Vista meaning “View”—this collection reimagines crowns as personal statements, combining surreal sunglasses and self-made headdresses to reshape how we see ourselves and the world. Through a seamless fusion of painterly craftsmanship, in-house production techniques, and Stable Diffusion software, Corona Vista blends the sprawling medieval landscapes and fantastical architecture of Chae’s Medieval series with the floral motifs and chic female protagonists inspired by Klara’s signature style. In this collection, the act of crowning oneself becomes a bold declaration: self-expression shapes not only how we’re seen, but how we see.

collections.name: WHO by tehranist (Women's Heaven Oasis)
collections.description: WOMEN'S HEAVEN OASISWOMEN'S HEAVEN OASIS is an NFT collection envisioning a future where women in the Middle East, Southwest Asia, and North Africa reclaim their autonomy and freedom. It challenges oppressive systems that force women to conform to restrictive dress codes, censor their expression, and deny their rights. Focusing on the struggles in Iran, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, and similar regions, it stands against regimes imposing mandatory hijabs and limiting personal freedom.This collection celebrates a society where women can live without censorship, reclaiming their voice, beauty, and power. Each NFT portrays vibrant depictions of women thriving in a world free from oppression—an oasis where they radiate strength and individuality. It’s a tribute to the dream of liberation for all women fighting for their right to exist on their terms, a beacon of hope for a future where their beauty is celebrated and their voices are heard.
